LV. ¹ Triumviros.] These, so called from their number, were per- sons appointed to over-see the prison, and execute the sentence of the senate or magistrates on criminals. They were called capitales, both from the nature of their office, and also to distinguish them from the Triumviri monetales, who had the charge of the mint3 and from the Triumviri nocturni, who had the charge of the watches for preventing fire in the night—M.
